      <body>
        <div>
            <pb facs="#TL-0396.jpg" n="part3_p004.jpg" xml:id="img_0004" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part3_p004.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_4_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>[391]
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>as such, is bad; conformism CAN be good, if it is historically founded and alive, as it still was
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>in England in the first half of this century. Conformism is bad if it extinguishes (as mass society
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>tends to do) the individual reactions, creativity of the individual person. Therefore perhaps if
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_2_tl_6" n="N005"/>this would be possible linguistically, one should distinguish patternization and conformism. The danger
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_2_tl_7" n="N006"/>certainly is patternization.
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_2_tl_8" n="N007"/>Now this was the result of our analysis. What does religion do in this situation? Why has
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_4_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>the relation of culture and religion become such a problem in our period, for the Western world,
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>for our generation? The answer is that religion is that dimension of experience which transcends
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>subjectivity and objectivity and cuts through the realm of subject and object, and that if religion
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>is brought down to the dimension in which subjects manage the objective world, religion
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>loses its meaning. This is a very simplified formula for an infinitely complex process. But in this
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>formula we can grasp the whole situation in a nutshell. Religion brought down to the level of
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>objectivation and then lost, whether attacked or defended. Both the defenders of religion
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_9" n="N008"/>on this level, and the critics of religion on this level, have LOST the meaning of religion!
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_10" n="N009"/>We can show this in the theoretical realms as well as in the practical realms.
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_11" n="N010"/>I showed it to you in the most expressive of all realms, that of the arts. You remember that
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_12" n="N011"/>level which I call the third level: religious symbols used in a naturalistic style. First in a man
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_13" n="N012"/>like Giotto, still the greatness of a religious substance expressed in naturalistic forms. Then step
               <lb facs="#facs_4_tr_1_tl_14" n="N013"/>by step the loss of this substance: it is wasted. And what is left is the objective world as we
            </p>
            
        </div>
